.TH "__flush_cache_one" 9 "__flush_cache_one" "May 2021" "Kernel Hacker's Manual" LINUX
.SH NAME
__flush_cache_one \- 
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B "void" __flush_cache_one
.BI "(unsigned long addr "  ","
.BI "unsigned long phys "  ","
.BI "unsigned long exec_offset "  ");"
.SH ARGUMENTS
.IP "addr" 12
address in memory mapped cache array
.IP "phys" 12
P1 address to flush (has to match tags if addr has 'A' bit
set i.e. associative write)
.IP "exec_offset" 12
set to 0x20000000 if flush has to be executed from P2
region else 0x0
.SH "DESCRIPTION"
The offset into the cache array implied by 'addr' selects the
'colour' of the virtual address range that will be flushed.  The
operation (purge/write-back) is selected by the lower 2 bits of
'phys'.
